# Calculer la matrice de corrlation
correlation_matrix <- cor(winequality_white)

# Visualiser la matrice de corrlation
corrplot(correlation_matrix, method = "circle")

Interpreting the results:

This correlation plot shows clearly the correlations between variables.

  • A positive correlation (shades of blue) means that if one the variables value increases, the other increases.
  • A negative correlation (shades of red) means that if one of the variables value increases, the other decreases.

Obviously, wine density is inversely correlated to alcohol content. This can be easily understood when comparing the density of ethanol to that of water:

  • Ethanol density : 0.7892 g/mL at 20C.
  • Water density : 0.9982 g/mL at 20C.

And indeed, if alcohol content is higher, the density lowers, which explains the strong negative correlation.

# Calculer la matrice de corrlation
correlation_pairs_matrix <- pairs(winequality_white)

# Test de normalit (Shapiro-Wilk)
shapiro.test(winequality_white$quality)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  winequality_white$quality
## W = 0.88904, p-value < 2.2e-16
# Crer une variable binaire pour la qualit
winequality_white$quality_binary <- ifelse(winequality_white$quality >= 6, "Good", "Bad")

# Effectuer le test t de Student
t.test(`alcohol` ~ quality_binary, data = winequality_white)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  alcohol by quality_binary
## t = -32.495, df = 4389.8, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group Bad and group Good is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -1.0596430 -0.9390554
## sample estimates:
##  mean in group Bad mean in group Good 
##            9.84953           10.84888
# Sparer les donnes en ensembles d'entranement et de test
set.seed(123)
trainIndex <- createDataPartition(winequality_white$quality, p = .8,
                                  list = FALSE,
                                  times = 1)
wineTrain <- winequality_white[ trainIndex,]
wineTest  <- winequality_white[-trainIndex,]

wineTrain <- wineTrain[, !(names(wineTrain) %in% c("quality_binary"))]

dim(wineTrain)
## [1] 3919   12
dim(wineTest)
## [1] 979  13

Decision Tree Model

# Entraner le modle avec un seul arbre de dcision

accuracy <- sum(tree_predictions == wineTest$quality) / nrow(wineTest)

Random Forest Model

# Entraner le modle de forts alatoires
model <- randomForest(quality ~ ., data = wineTrain)

# Prdire sur l'ensemble de test
predictions <- predict(model, wineTest)

# Arrondir les prdictions pour obtenir des nombres entiers
rounded_predictions <- round(predictions)

# Afficher les prdictions
head(rounded_predictions)
## 1 2 3 4 5 6 
## 6 6 6 6 6 6
# valuer le modle
eval <- postResample(pred = rounded_predictions, obs = wineTest$quality)

# Afficher les mtriques d'valuation
eval
##      RMSE  Rsquared       MAE 
## 0.6580995 0.4600931 0.3677222

Interprtation

RMSE

Le RMSE mesure lcart moyen entre les valeurs prdites par le modle et les valeurs relles. Une valeur de RMSE plus faible indique un meilleur ajustement du modle aux donnes. Ici, la valeur est de 0.6581, ce qui signifie quen moyenne, les prdictions du modle scartent de 0.6581 units des valeurs relles.

Rsquared

Le coefficient de dtermination, ou R-squared, reprsente la proportion de la variance de la variable dpendante qui est prvisible partir des variables indpendantes. Un R-squared de 1 signifie que le modle explique parfaitement la variance des donnes, tandis quun R-squared de 0 signifie que le modle nexplique aucune variance. Ici, la valeur est de 0.4601, indiquant que le modle explique environ 46.01% de la variance dans la qualit du vin.

MAE

Le MAE mesure lerreur moyenne absolue entre les prdictions et les valeurs relles. Contrairement au RMSE, il ne pnalise pas autant les grandes erreurs. Ici, la valeur est de 0.3677, ce qui signifie quen moyenne, les prdictions du modle scartent de 0.3677 units des valeurs relles.
